, Bavaria, Germany":"Hohenberg, Herrieden, Ansbach, Bavaria, Germany","Grünbach, , , Sachsen, Allemagne":"Grünbach, Vogtlandkreis, Saxony, Germany","Hohenberg, Schwarzwaldkreis, Württemberg, Duitsland":"Hohenberg, Durbach, Kreis Offenburg, Baden, Germany","Grünbach, Vogtlandkreis, Saxony, Germany":"Grünbach, Vogtlandkreis, Saxony, Germany","Grünberg, Kirchdorf, Oberösterreich, Oostenrijk":"Grünberg, Kirchdorf, Upper Austria, Austria","nameMeanings":[{"name":"von","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Grünberg","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Pnina, Anat, Avraham, Emanuel, Shoshana.  German Angelika, Wolf, Wolfgang.","Jewish (Ashkenazic; <b>Grünberg</b>): artificial name from German <i>grün</i> ‘green’ + <i>Berg</i> ‘mountain, hill’.","German (<b>Grünberg</b>): habitational name from any of numerous places called Grünberg. Compare   Greenberg  ,   Gruenberg  , and   Greenhill  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Greenberg","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Meyer, Hyman, Emanuel, Ari, Chaim, Isadore, Arie, Avrohom, Avrom, Moshe.","Americanized form of Jewish and German <b>Grünberg</b> ‘green mountain’ (see   Grunberg  )."]},{"name":"Grueneberg","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Fritz, Hermann.","German (<b>Grüneberg</b>): variant of <b>Grünberg</b> (see   Grunberg  )."]},{"name":"Gruenberg","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Helmuth, Juergen, Kurt.","Jewish (Ashkenazic) and German (<b>Grünberg</b>): see   Grunberg  ."]},{"name":"Grinberg","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Yakov, Isaak, Meyer, Moises, Avram, Borukh, Chaim, Chiam, Fayvel.  Russian Boris, Aleksandr, Mikhail, Vladimir, Grigoriy, Igor, Leonid, Lev, Yefim, Arkady, Oleg, Anatoly.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): variant of <b>Grünberg</b> (see   Grunberg  ).","Swedish: ornamental name composed of an unexplained first element + <i>berg</i> ‘mountain, hill’."]},{"name":"Greenberger","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Isidor, Binyomin, Mendel, Meyer, Zeev.","Americanized form of Jewish (Ashkenazic) and German <b>Grünberger</b>. As a Jewish surname it is artificial (see   Grunberg  ), while the German name is habitational name for someone from any of numerous places called Grünberg + the habitational suffix <i>-er</i>."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Kunigunde von Grünberg was born in 1145, in Grünberg, Kirchdorf, Upper Austria, Austria, her father, Markwart von Grünbach II, was 46 and her mother, Tuta VON LAUDA, was 15. She had at least 1 son with Graf Burkhard von Hohenberg III. She died after 1176, in Hohenberg, Durbach, Kreis Offenburg, Baden, Germany."},"et":{"1145–na 1176":"1145–pärast 1176","1130–1166":"1130–1166","1145–1176":"1145–1176","1147–1190":"1147–1190","1150–1190":"1150–1190","1148–1193":"1148–1193","1176–1225":"1176–1225","1100–1164":"1100–1164","1130–1176":"1130–1176","1190":"1190","na 1176":"pärast 1176","9 February 1164":"9. veebruar 1164","1176":"1176","1164":"1164","1130":"1130","22 APR 1176":"22. aprill 1176","1150":"1150","1193":"1193","1225":"1225","1148":"1148","1147":"1147","1145":"1145","1100":"1100","1166":"1166","Hohenberg, Ansbach, Bavaria, Germany":"Hohenberg, Herrieden, Landkreis Ansbach, Bayern, Saksamaa","Grünbach, , , Sachsen, Allemagne":"Grünbach, Vogtlandkreis, Sachsen, Saksamaa","Hohenberg, Schwarzwaldkreis, Württemberg, Duitsland":"Hohenberg, Durbach, Kreis Offenburg, Baden, Saksamaa",